    <li><%= DOC.modules.render('Base/Visibility/Responsive/Hide_Above') %></li>
</ul>

<h3>Examples</h3>

<h4>Basic Visibility</h4>

<p>The <code>.hide</code> class hides content from view and screenreaders. Applying the <code>.hide</code> class on an element is similar to calling <code>$(ele).hide()</code> in jQuery. Both are just slightly shorthand for the style property <code>display:none</code>.</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="hide"&gt;&lt;!-- hidden content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<h4>Visibility for Accessibility Tools Only</h4>

<p>The <code>.hide-accessible</code> class may be used to define an element that will only show with accessibility tools such as screen readers.</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="hide-accessible"&gt;&lt;!-- hidden content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<p>The <code>.focusable</code> class may be used in addition to the <code>.hide-accessible</code> class in cases where, in addition to accessibility tools, if one applies focus on the element, it will become visible.</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="hide-accessible focusable"&gt;&lt;!-- hidden content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<h4>Visibility based on Media Query Support</h4>

<p>The <code>.hide-media-query</code> class may be used to define an element that will only show if media queries <em>are not supported</em> by the browser. This class is thus similar to the <code>noscript</code> tag used to show content when Javascript isn't available.</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="hide"&gt;&lt;!-- hidden content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<h4>Visibility based on Viewport Size</h4>

<p>Generally, responsive designs should try to avoid coding explicitly for different screen sizes, but in some cases, this is necessary. WebBlocks thus provides a set of classes <code>.hide-X</code> and <code>.hide-above-X</code> that allows one to define the viewport sizes in which a given element is shown.</p>

<p class="text-danger">It should be noted that these classes should not be used with elements that have styles assigned by nth-child selectors, such as <code>.panel-X</code>.</p>

<p>An element with <code>.hide-xxsmall</code> will appear above <code>$breakpoint-xxsmall</code>, whereas an element <code>.hide-above-xxsmall</code> will only appear below <code>$breakpoint-xxsmall</code>:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="hide-xxsmall"&gt;
    &lt;!-- show above xxsmall --&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="hide-above-xxsmall"&gt;
    &lt;!-- show at and below xxsmall --&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<div class="example row hide-xxsmall">
    <div class="success panel-6">.hide-xxsmall</div>
    <div class="danger panel-6">.hide-above-xxsmall</div>
</div>
<div class="example row hide-above-xxsmall">
    <div class="danger panel-6">.hide-xxsmall</div>
    <div class="success panel-6">.hide-above-xxsmall</div>
</div>

